y/ts/v3n09.htm#706}}.\n*{{Citation | editor-last = Smith | editor-first = Joseph Fielding | author-link = Joseph Fielding Smith |title=Teachings of the Prophet Joseph Smith |publisher=[[Deseret Book Company]] |year=1976 |isbn=0-87747-665-9 |others=(index and concordance by [[Robert J. Matthews]])| title-link = Teachings of the Prophet Joseph Smith }}\n*{{Citation |last=Williams |first=Drew |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Understanding Mormonism |publisher=Alpha |year=2003 |isbn=0-02-864491-3}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{Citation |last=Williams |first=Drew |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Understanding Mormonism |publisher=Alpha |year=2003 |isbn=0-02-864491-3}}\n*{{Citation |last=Shipps |first=Jan | author-link=Jan Shipps |title=Sojourner in the Promised Land: Forty Years Among the Mormons |publisher=[[University of Illinois Press]] |year=2000 |isbn=0-252-02590-3}}\n*{{Citation |last=Shipps |first=Jan | author-link=Jan Shipps |title=Mormonism: The Story of a New Religious Tradition |publisher=[[University of Illinois Press]] |year=1987 |isbn=0-252-01417-0}}\n*{{Citation |last1=Ostling |first1=Richard |author1-link=Richard Ostling |last2=Ostling |first2=Joan K. |year=2000 |title=Mormon America: The Power and the Promise |publisher=[[HarperSanFrancisco]] |edition=1st |isbn=0-06-066372-3 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/mormonamericapow00ostl }}\n*{{Citation |last1=Riess |first1=Jana | author1-link = Jana Riess |last2=Bigelow |first2=Christopher Kimball |title=Mormonism For Dummies |publisher=For Dummies |year=2005 |isbn=0-7645-7195-8}}\n*{{Citation |last=Newell |first=Coke |author-link=Coke Newell |year=2001 |title=Latter Days: An Insider's Guide to Mormonism, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints |publisher=[[St. Martin's Griffin]] |isbn=0-312-28043-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/latterdays00coke }}\n*{{Citation |last=Stark |first=Rodney | author-link=Rodney Stark |year=2005 |title=The Rise of Mormonism |publisher=Columbia University Press |isbn=0-231-13634-X|title-link=The Rise of Mormonism }}\n*{{Citation |last=Prince |first=Gregory | author-link=Gregory Prince |year=2005 |title=David O. McKay and the Rise of Modern Mormonism |publisher=[[University of Utah Press]] |isbn=0-87480-822-7|title-link=David O. McKay and the Rise of Modern Mormonism }}\n*{{Citation |last=Foreman |first=Grant | author-link=Grant Foreman |year=1935 |title=Missionaries of the Latter Day Saints Church in Indian Territory  |publisher=[[Createspace]] |isbn=978-1533469199}}\n*{{Citation |last=Winder |first=Michael | author-link=Michael K. Winder |year=2007 |title=Presidents and Prophets |publisher=[[Covenant Communications]] |isbn=978-1-59811-452-2|title-link=Presidents and Prophets }}\n*{{Citation |last=Kidd |first=Clark | author-link = |year=1998 |title=A Convert's Guide to Mormon Life: A Guidebook for New Members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints |publisher=[[Deseret Book Company]] |isbn=1-57008-520-X}}\n*{{Citation |last=Bushman |first=Richard | author-link=Richard Bushman |year=2008 |title=Mormonism: A Very Short Introduction |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-531030-6}}\n*{{Citation |last=Brase |first=Brad | author-link= |year=1998 |title=Why Would Anyone Join the Mormon Church? |publisher=Bonneville Publishing Company |isbn=1-55517-387-X}}\n*{{Citation |last=Brown |first=Dennis |author-link= |year=2008 |title=Evidences of the True Church |publisher=Cedar Fort |isbn=978-0-88290-712-3 |url=https://archive.org/details/evidencesoftruec00denn }}\n*{{Citation |last=Denison |first=Alan |author-link= |year=2002 |title=Guess Who Wants to Have You for Lunch? |publisher=[[Foundation for Apologetic Information & Research]] |isbn=1-893036-05-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/guesswhowantstoh00alan }}\n*{{Citation |last=Eliason |first=Eric | author-link= |year=2001 |title=Mormons and Mormonism: an introduction to an American world religion |publisher=[[University of Illinois Press]] |isbn=0-252-06912-9}}\n*{{Citation |last=Millet |first=Robert |author-link=Robert L. Millet |year=1998 |title=Latter-day Christianity: 10 Basic Issues |publisher=Maxwell Institute |isbn=0934893322 |url=https://archive.org/details/latterdaychristi00mill }}\n*{{Citation |last=Millet |first=Robert | author-link=Robert L. Millet |year=2008 |title=Magnifying Priesthood Power |publisher=Cedar Fort |isbn=978-0-88290-779-6}}\n*{{Citation |last=Millet |first=Robert | author-link=Robert L. Millet |year=2007 |title=The vision of Mormonism: pressing the boundaries of Christianity |publisher=Paragon House |isbn=978-1-55778-868-9}}\n*{{Citation |last=Neilson |first=Reid |author-link=Reid Larkin Neilson |year=2008 |title=Global Mormonism in the 21st Century |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]] |isbn=978-0-8425-2696-8 |url=http://rsc.byu.edu/archived/global-mormonism-21st-century |access-date=February 8, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106233229/http://rsc.byu.edu/archived/global-mormonism-21st-century |archive-date=January 6, 2015 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{Citation |last=Shuster |first=Eric | author-link= |year=2010 |title=The Biblical Roots of Mormonism |publisher=Cedar Fort, Inc. |isbn=978-1-59955-406-8}}\n*{{Citation |last=Scott |first=Tom | author-link= |year=2012 |title=It's True: An Evangelical Pastor's Journey to Truth in the Mormon Church |publisher=Brigham Distributing |isbn=978-0983603047}}\n*{{Citation |last=Webb |first=Stephen H.  | author-link=Stephen H. Webb |year=2013 |title=Mormon Christianity: What Other Christians Can Learn From the Latter-day Saints |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0199316816}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|s=no|v=no|b=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|En-The_Church_of_Jesus_Christ_of_Latter-day_Saints-article.ogg|2007-01-12}}\n\n'''Official church websites'''\n* [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/ ChurchofJesusChrist.org] \u2013 Official church website\n* [http://www.comeuntochrist.org ComeUntoChrist.org] \u2013 Official church website, with information about basic beliefs. (formerly Mormon.org)\n* [https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org Newsroom] \u2013 Official church website, with news of the church and  official church statements.\n* [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/China The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in China] \u2013 Official site on members in China\n\n'''Other sites'''\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Church+of+Jesus+Christ+of+Latter-day+Saints}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |search=(\"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter day Saints\" OR \"Mormon Church\" OR \"LDS Church\")}}\n\n{{Latter-day Saints}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Links to related articles\n|list =\n{{LDSsites}}\n{{LDSpageants}}\n{{Latter Day Saint movement}}\n{{Christianity footer}}\n|state =autocollapse\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Church Of Jesus Christ Of Latter-Day Saints}}\n[[Category:1830 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Christian denominations established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Joseph Smith]]\n[[Category:Organizations that oppose same-sex marriage]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1830]]\n[[Category:The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]\n", "name_user": "0~Green~Starlight~0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Church_of_Jesus_Christ_of_Latter-day_Saints"}
{"title_page": "New-York Central College, McGrawville", "text_new": "'''New-York Central College''', commonly called '''New-York Central College, McGrawville''', was an institution of higher learning founded by [[Cyrus Pitt Grosvenor]] and other anti-slavery [[Baptists]] in 1849 in [[McGraw, New York]] (at the time called McGrawville; not modern [[McGrawville, New York]]).<ref name=\"passic\">{{cite web|last=Passic|first=Frank|title=Cyrus Pitt Gosvenor|url=http://www.albionmich.com/history/histor_notebook/951001.shtml|publisher=Albion Historical Society Collection|accessdate=28 November 2010}}</ref> It lasted about 10 years. As put by the author of a modern study, \"A little town tried to create a place without any prejudice, and it did make a difference. It created humanitarians and heroes in a time where nothing else existed like this.\"<ref>{{cite article\n|title=New York Central College the topic of McGraw author's new book\n|date=October 2, 2017\n|first=Robert\n|last=Creenan\n|newspaper=Cortland Standard}}</ref>\n\nGrosvenor \"proposed a 'free institution,' for the 'literary, scientific, moral, and physical education of both sexes and of all classes of youth.'\" The school's [[curriculum]] included [[Classical education movement|classical education]] as well as [[agricultural science]]. The Rev. Grosvenor served as the school's first President, 1849\u20131850.<ref name=\"passic\"/> A newspaper announcement in 1854 gives the President as Leonard G. Calkins, with the note that the [[Manual labor school|Manual Labor Department]] was \"under the supervision of Luther Wellington, a Practical Farmer, a kind and benevolent man, on a farm of {{convert|187|acre}}.\" Under the \"careful training\" of the President students took a Rhetorical Class \"with daily exercises in Extemporaneous Speaking\", \"not to be overlooked in this day of 'public speaking'\".<ref>{{cite news\n|title=New York Central College\n|newspaper=[[The Liberator (newspaper)|The Liberator]]\n|date=March 24, 1854\n|page=3\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34217719/announcement_of_new_york_central_college/}}</ref>\n\nThe college was modeled after [[Oberlin College|Oberlin]], which in 1835 began admitting blacks and in 1837 women. New-York Central College was the first college in the U.S. ''founded'' specifically to educate all students: black and white, male and female. It was also the first to have African-American professors: [[Charles L. Reason]], who was an [[alumnus]], [[William G. Allen]], a graduate of [[Oneida Institute]], another short-lived school which was a predecessor of the College, and [[George Boyer Vashon]], the first African-American graduate of [[Oberlin College|Oberlin]]. Reason was the first black college professor in the country. Allen was Professor of Rhetoric and Greek; in 1850, when he was appointed, be was \"well known as a lecturer upon the origin, literature, and destiny of the African race.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|title=By Telegraph\n|newspaper=[[Newport Daily News]] ([[Newport, Rhode Island]])\n|date=December 16, 1850\n|page=2\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/361769/william_g_allen_law_student/}}</ref>\n\nIn 1851 it was one of 11 colleges to receive New York State legislative funding; it received $1,500, the same amount as New York University, Fordham University, [[Hamilton College]], and [[Colgate University|Madison University]] (Colgate).<ref>{{cite news\n|title=New York Legislature\n|date=June 18, 1851\n|newspaper=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]\n|page=3\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32719775/new_york_legislature_appropriations/}}</ref>\n\nStudents and professors were not allowed to use alcohol or (much more unusual) tobacco.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Untitled\n|newspaper=The Advocate ([[Buffalo, New York]])\n|date=July 24, 1851\n|page=3\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32753987/no_alcohol_or_tobacco_at_new_york/}}</ref>\n\nIn 1856 there were 226 students and 9 faculty.<ref name=Place>{{citation\n|title=Personal recollections\n|first=Frank\n|last=Place\n|url=https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/id/240/rec/12\n|accessdate=December 24, 2018}}</ref> Approximately 50% were African-American.\n\n==Hostility to the College==\nBecause of its equalitarian treatment of blacks, which at the time was called \"[[amalgamation (race)|amalgamation]]\",<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Amalgamation\n|newspaper=[[Middlebury Register]] ([[Middlebury, Vermont]])\n|date=May 11, 1853\n|page=2\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33791488/marriage_of_william_g_allen/}}</ref> the \"nigger college at McGrawville\", as it was called,<ref name=Place/> received a lot of public vituperation. A New York legislator said that rather than giving a state appropriation to that \"vile sink of pollution\", it would be better given to \"a mob that will raze it to the ground\", because it \"was at war with every principle of American liberty\".<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Literature in the Legislature\n|newspaper=[[New York Post|Evening Post]] (New York, N.Y.)\n|date=June 28, 1851\n|page=2\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32754122/on_the_new_york_legislature_1851_new/}}</ref> The [[New-York Tribune]] called it a \"treasonable college\", an \"obnoxious edifice\" where, \"if things are suffered to go on at this rate, this whole region will become infected with Abolitionism; the contagion of Free Speech will spread til the Fugitive Slave law will become a nullity and the Union will collapse!\"<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Central College Anniversary\n|newspaper=[[New-York Tribune]]\n|date=July 29, 1856\n|page=6\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32754633/new_york_central_college_anniversary/}}</ref>\n\n===William Allen affair===\nA scandal was caused when African-American professor [[William G. Allen]] became engaged to a white student, Mary King. To escape violent repercussions, Allen fled to [[New York City]], where he was joined by his [[fianc\u00e9e]]; they married and immediately left for England, never to return. This event exacerbated already lingering social and political opposition to the school. (Marlene Parks has published a collection of press clippings, which show the hostility.<ref>{{cite book\n|title=New York Central College, 1849-1860, McGrawville, N.Y. : the first college in the U.S. to employ black professors\n|first=Marlene K.\n|last=Parks\n|publisher=McGraw Historical Society, through [[CreateSpace]] Independent Publishing Platform\n|year=2017\n|isbn=9781517478124}}</ref>)\n\nA clipping of 1854 shows him lecturing to an anti-slavery meeting in [[Manchester]], with other lectures in the vicinity on \"'The origin, past history, and literature of the African race'; 'The probable destiny of the African race', &amp;o. &amp;o.\" A letter from [[Lord Shaftesbury]] said he \"sympathises most heartily with Professor Allen, and sincerely wishes him suooess in his undertaking. It will give Lord Shaftesbury great pleasure to assist in any way that he can a gentleman of the coloured race, who is a hundred times wiser, and better, than his white oppressors.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Local News. Anti Slavery Meeting\n|newspaper=[[Manchester Times|Manchester Weekly Times and Examiner]] ([[Manchester, England]])\n|date=November 1, 1854\n|page=5\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32077507/antislavery_talk_by_william_g_allen/}}</ref>\n\n===Closure===\nThe school was later denied funding by the New York State Legislature, and it was bankrupt by 1858.<ref name=Elbert>{{cite book\n|contribution=Introduction\n|title=The American prejudice against color : William G. Allen, Mary King, and Louisa May Alcott\n|editor-first=Sarah\n|editor-last=Elbert\n|location=Boston\n|publisher=[[Northeastern University Press]]\n|date=2002\n|isbn=9781555535452}}</ref>{{rp|14}}\n\nFacing [[bankruptcy]], the school was put into the hands of the wealthy activist [[Gerrit Smith]], who lived nearby, in [[Peterboro, New York|Peterboro]]. A [[smallpox]] epidemic struck McGrawville in 1860. The effects of the outbreak, coupled with the lingering social and political opposition and financial difficulties, caused the college to close that same year. Another source says it closed in 1859.<ref name=passic/>\n\nThe [[New York Central Railroad]], with which there is no known connection, began in 1853.\n\n===Central Academy===\n[[Daniel S. Lamont]], Secretary of War under President [[Grover Cleveland]], was from McGraw, and studied as a child at the Central Academy, \"the successor of a queer institution, known as the New York Central College, established by Gerrit Smith and other abolitionists, for the education of boys and girls without regard to color.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Col. Daniel Lamont\n|newspaper=[[South Bend Tribune]] ([[South Bend, Indiana]])\n|date=March 14, 1893\n|page=6\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34209193/the_south_bend_tribune/}}</ref> Lamont was born in 1851.\n\n==Alumni==\n*[[Charles L. Reason]], first [[African American]] to teach college \n*[[Angeline Stickney]], American [[Women's suffrage in the United States|suffragist]], [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]], and [[mathematician]], who taught at New-York Central College. Among her students was her eventual husband, astronomer [[Asaph Hall]]. [[Stickney (crater)|Stickney]], the largest crater on Mars's moon [[Phobos (moon)|Phobos]], is named for her.\n*[[Asaph Hall]], astronomer, known for his discovery of the [[moons of Mars]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Juan Latino]], a black college professor in sixteenth-century Spain\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book\n|title=New York Central College, Volume 3. Condensed Version of Volumes 1 and 2\n|first=Marlene K.\n|last=Parks\n|publisher=McGraw Historical Society\n|year=2018\n|isbn=9781729614884}}\n* {{cite article\n|title=McGraw producers to screen film on interracial college to DC\n|date=January 16, 2017\n|first=Todd R.\n|last=McAdam\n|url=http://cortlandstandard.net/2017/01/16/mcgraw-producers-to-screen-film-on-interracial-college-to-dc/\n|newspaper=Cortland Standard}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=New York Central College, 1849--1860, McGrawville, N.Y. : Volume 1\n|first=Marlene K.\n|last=Parks\n|publisher=McGraw Historical Society\n|year=2017\n|others=Part 1. Newspaper Articles concerning the College, November 1847\u2014December, 1849. Part 2. Alphabetical Biographical Sketches Abbott\u2014Lyons. Part 3. Newspaper Articles concerning the College, March, 1850\u2014December, 1850.\n|isbn=9781517478124}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=New York Central College, 1849--1860, McGrawville, N.Y. : Volume 2\n|first=Marlene K.\n|last=Parks\n|publisher=McGraw Historical Society\n|year=2017\n|others=Part 1. Newspaper Articles concerning the College, January, 1851\u2014December, 1853. Part 2. Alphabetical Biographical Sketches Lyons\u2014Young. Part 3. Newspaper Articles concerning the College, March, 1854\u2014August, 1861.\n|isbn=9781548505752}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=Pre-Cornell and Early Cornell VIII. Cornell's Three Precursors. I. New York Central College\n|last=Wright\n|first=Albert Hazen\n|publisher=[[Cornell University]]\n|year=1960\n|url=https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/id/208/rec/5}}\n\n==Video==\n* {{cite video\n|title=New York Central College: An Experiment in Education in McGrawville 1848-1860\n|first1=Carl\n|first2=Mary\n|last1=Kimberly\n|last2=Kimberly\n|publisher=Cortland County Historical Society\n|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=GalCjbMVgfk&t=1s\n|year=2018}}\n\n==Primary sources==\n* {{cite book\n|title=American Baptist Free Mission Society report on the New York Central College, McGrawville, NY\n|year=1850\n|url=https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/id/238/rec/1}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=Catalogue of the officers and students of New-York Central College, for the year 1852\u20133, McGrawville, NY\n|location=[[Homer, New York]]\n|year=1853\n|url=https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/id/236/rec/2}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=Commencement exercises of New York Central College\n|date=July 11, 1855\n|url=https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/id/235/rec/3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/search/searchterm/New%20York%20Central%20College/field/relatig/mode/exact/conn/and/order/date McGraw Historical Society collection of New-York Central College material]\n<!--https://www.newspapers.com/image/32260714/?terms=%22central%2Bcollege%22%2Bthousand-->\n{{coord missing|New York (state)}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct universities and colleges in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Baptist universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1849]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions disestablished in 1860]]\n[[Category:Education in Cortland County, New York]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1860 disestablishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Agricultural universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Antebellum educational institutions that admitted African Americans]]\n[[Category:Recipients of aid from Gerrit Smith]]\n[[Category:American manual labor schools]]\n", "text_old": "'''New-York Central College''', commonly called '''New-York Central College, McGrawville''', was an institution of higher learning founded by [[Cyrus Pitt Grosvenor]] and other anti-slavery [[Baptists]] in 1849 in [[McGraw, New York]] (at the time called McGrawville; not modern [[McGrawville, New York]]).<ref name=\"passic\">{{cite web|last=Passic|first=Frank|title=Cyrus Pitt Gosvenor|url=http://www.albionmich.com/history/histor_notebook/951001.shtml|publisher=Albion Historical Society Collection|accessdate=28 November 2010}}</ref> It lasted about 10 years. As put by the author of a modern study, \"A little town tried to create a place without any prejudice, and it did make a difference. It created humanitarians and heroes in a time where nothing else existed like this.\"<ref>{{cite article\n|title=New York Central College the topic of McGraw author's new book\n|date=October 2, 2017\n|first=Robert\n|last=Creenan\n|newspaper=Cortland Standard}}</ref>\n\nGrosvenor \"proposed a 'free institution,' for the 'literary, scientific, moral, and physical education of both sexes and of all classes of youth.'\" The school's [[curriculum]] included [[Classical education movement|classical education]] as well as [[agricultural science]]. The Rev. Grosvenor served as the school's first President, 1849\u20131850.<ref name=\"passic\"/> A newspaper announcement in 1854 gives the President as Leonard G. Calkins, with the note that the [[Manual labor school|Manual Labor Department]] was \"under the supervision of Luther Wellington, a Practical Farmer, a kind and benevolent man, on a farm of {{convert|187|acre}}.\" Under the \"careful training\" of the President students took a Rhetorical Class \"with daily exercises in Extemporaneous Speaking\", \"not to be overlooked in this day of 'public speaking'\".<ref>{{cite news\n|title=New York Central College\n|newspaper=[[The Liberator (newspaper)|The Liberator]]\n|date=March 24, 1854\n|page=3\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34217719/announcement_of_new_york_central_college/}}</ref>\n\nThe college was modeled after [[Oberlin College|Oberlin]], which in 1835 began admitting blacks and in 1837 women. New-York Central College was the first college in the U.S. ''founded'' specifically to educate all students: black and white, male and female. It was also the first to have African-American professors: [[Charles L. Reason]], who was an [[alumnus]], [[William G. Allen]], a graduate of [[Oneida Institute]], another short-lived school which was a predecessor of the College, and [[George Boyer Vashon]], the first African-American graduate of [[Oberlin College|Oberlin]]. Reason was the first black college professor in the country. Allen was Professor of Rhetoric and Greek; in 1850, when he was appointed, be was \"well known as a lecturer upon the origin, literature, and destiny of the African race.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|title=By Telegraph\n|newspaper=[[Newport Daily News]] ([[Newport, Rhode Island]])\n|date=December 16, 1850\n|page=2\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/361769/william_g_allen_law_student/}}</ref>\n\nIn 1851 it was one of 11 colleges to receive New York State legislative funding; it received $1,500, the same amount as New York University, Fordham University, [[Hamilton College]], and [[Colgate University|Madison University]] (Colgate).<ref>{{cite news\n|title=New York Legislature\n|date=June 18, 1851\n|newspaper=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]\n|page=3\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32719775/new_york_legislature_appropriations/}}</ref>\n\nStudents and professors were not allowed to use alcohol or (much more unusual) tobacco.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Untitled\n|newspaper=The Advocate ([[Buffalo, New York]])\n|date=July 24, 1851\n|page=3\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32753987/no_alcohol_or_tobacco_at_new_york/}}</ref>\n\nIn 1856 there were 226 students and 9 faculty.<ref name=Place>{{citation\n|title=Personal recollections\n|first=Frank\n|last=Place\n|url=https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/id/240/rec/12\n|accessdate=December 24, 2018}}</ref> Approximately 50% were African-American.\n\n==Hostility to the College==\nBecause of its equalitarian treatment of blacks, which at the time was called \"[[amalgamation (race)|amalgamation]]\",<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Amalgamation\n|newspaper=[[Middlebury Register]] ([[Middlebury, Vermont]])\n|date=May 11, 1853\n|page=2\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33791488/marriage_of_william_g_allen/}}</ref> the \"nigger college at McGrawville\", as it was called,<ref name=Place/> received a lot of public vituperation. A New York legislator said that rather than giving a state appropriation to that \"vile sink of pollution\", it would be better given to \"a mob that will raze it to the ground\", because it \"was at war with every principle of American liberty\".<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Literature in the Legislature\n|newspaper=[[New York Post|Evening Post]] (New York, N.Y.)\n|date=June 28, 1851\n|page=2\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32754122/on_the_new_york_legislature_1851_new/}}</ref> The [[New-York Tribune]] called it a \"treasonable college\", an \"obnoxious edifice\" where, \"if things are suffered to go on at this rate, this whole region will become infected with Abolitionism; the contagion of Free Speech will spread til the Fugitive Slave law will become a nullity and the Union will collapse!\"<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Central College Anniversary\n|newspaper=[[New-York Tribune]]\n|date=July 29, 1856\n|page=6\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32754633/new_york_central_college_anniversary/}}</ref>\n\n===William Allen affair===\nA scandal was caused when African-American professor [[William G. Allen]] became engaged to a white student, Mary King. To escape violent repercussions, Allen fled to [[New York City]], where he was joined by his [[fianc\u00e9e]]; they married and immediately left for England, never to return. This event exacerbated already lingering social and political opposition to the school. (Marlene Parks has published a collection of press clippings, which show the hostility.<ref>{{cite book\n|title=New York Central College, 1849-1860, McGrawville, N.Y. : the first college in the U.S. to employ black professors\n|first=Marlene K.\n|last=Parks\n|publisher=McGraw Historical Society, through [[CreateSpace]] Independent Publishing Platform\n|year=2017\n|isbn=9781517478124}}</ref>)\n\nA clipping of 1854 shows him lecturing to an anti-slavery meeting in [[Manchester]], with other lectures in the vicinity on \"'The origin, past history, and literature of the African race'; 'The probable destiny of the African race', &amp;o. &amp;o.\" A letter from [[Lord Shaftesbury]] said he \"sympathises most heartily with Professor Allen, and sincerely wishes him suooess in his undertaking. It will give Lord Shaftesbury great pleasure to assist in any way that he can a gentleman of the coloured race, who is a hundred times wiser, and better, than his white oppressors.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Local News. Anti Slavery Meeting\n|newspaper=[[Manchester Times|Manchester Weekly Times and Examiner]] ([[Manchester, England]])\n|date=November 1, 1854\n|page=5\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32077507/antislavery_talk_by_william_g_allen/}}</ref>\n\n===Closure===\nThe school was later denied funding by the New York State Legislature, and it was bankrupt by 1858.<ref name=Elbert>{{cite book\n|contribution=Introduction\n|title=The American prejudice against color : William G. Allen, Mary King, and Louisa May Alcott\n|editor-first=Sarah\n|editor-last=Elbert\n|location=Boston\n|publisher=[[Northeastern University Press]]\n|date=2002\n|isbn=9781555535452}}</ref>{{rp|14}}\n\nFacing [[bankruptcy]], the school was put into the hands of the wealthy activist [[Gerrit Smith]], who lived nearby, in [[Peterboro, New York|Peterboro]]. A [[smallpox]] epidemic struck McGrawville in 1860. The effects of the outbreak, coupled with the lingering social and political opposition and financial difficulties, caused the college to close that same year. Another source says it closed in 1859.<ref name=passic/>\n\nThe [[New York Central Railroad]], with which there is no known connection, began in 1853.\n\n===Central Academy===\n[[Daniel S. Lamont]], Secretary of War under President [[Grover Cleveland]], was from McGraw, and studied as a child at the Central Academy, \"the successor of a queer institution, known as the New York Central College, established by Gerrit Smith and other abolitionists, for the education of boys and girls without regard to color.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Col. Daniel Lamont\n|newspaper=[[South Bend Tribune]] ([[South Bend, Indiana]])\n|date=March 14, 1893\n|page=6\n|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34209193/the_south_bend_tribune/}}</ref> Lamont was born in 1851.\n\n==Alumni==\n*[[Charles L. Reason]], first [[African American]] to teach college \n*[[Angeline Stickney]], American [[Women's suffrage in the United States|suffragist]], [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]], and [[mathematician]], who taught at New-York Central College. Among her students was her eventual husband, astronomer [[Asaph Hall]]. [[Stickney (crater)|Stickney]], the largest crater on Mars's moon [[Phobos (moon)|Phobos]], is named for her.\n*[[Asaph Hall]], astronomer, known for his discovery of the [[moons of Mars]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Juan Latino]], a black college professor in sixteenth-century Spain\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book\n|title=New York Central College, Volume 3. Condensed Version of Volumes 1 and 2\n|first=Marlene K.\n|last=Parks\n|publisher=McGraw Historical Society\n|year=2018\n|isbn=9781729614884}}\n* {{cite article\n|title=McGraw producers to screen film on interracial college to DC\n|date=January 16, 2017\n|first=Todd R.\n|last=McAdam\n|url=http://cortlandstandard.net/2017/01/16/mcgraw-producers-to-screen-film-on-interracial-college-to-dc/\n|newspaper=Cortland Standard}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=New York Central College, 1849--1860, McGrawville, N.Y. : Volume 1\n|first=Marlene K.\n|last=Parks\n|publisher=McGraw Historical Society\n|year=2017\n|others=Part 1. Newspaper Articles concerning the College, November 1847\u2014December, 1849. Part 2. Alphabetical Biographical Sketches Abbott\u2014Lyons. Part 3. Newspaper Articles concerning the College, March, 1850\u2014December, 1850.\n|isbn=9781517478124}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=New York Central College, 1849--1860, McGrawville, N.Y. : Volume 2\n|first=Marlene K.\n|last=Parks\n|publisher=McGraw Historical Society\n|year=2017\n|others=Part 1. Newspaper Articles concerning the College, January, 1851\u2014December, 1853. Part 2. Alphabetical Biographical Sketches Lyons\u2014Young. Part 3. Newspaper Articles concerning the College, March, 1854\u2014August, 1861.\n|isbn=9781548505752}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=Pre-Cornell and Early Cornell VIII. Cornell's Three Precursors. I. New York Central College\n|last=Wright\n|first=Albert Hazen\n|publisher=[[Cornell University]]\n|year=1960\n|url=https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/id/208/rec/5}}\n\n==Video==\n* {{cite video\n|title=New York Central College: An Experiment in Education in McGrawville 1848-1860\n|first1=Carl\n|first2=Mary\n|last1=Kimberly\n|last2=Kimberly\n|publisher=Cortland County Historical Society\n|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=GalCjbMVgfk&t=1s\n|year=2018}}\n\n==Primary sources==\n* {{cite book\n|title=American Baptist Free Mission Society report on the New York Central College, McGrawville, NY\n|year=1850\n|url=https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/id/238/rec/1}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=Catalogue of the officers and students of New-York Central College, for the year 1852\u20133, McGrawville, NY\n|location=[[Homer, New York]]\n|year=1853\n|url=https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/id/236/rec/2}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=Commencement exercises of New York Central College\n|date=July 11, 1855\n|url=https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/id/235/rec/3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://cdm16694.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/NYMHG/search/searchterm/New%20York%20Central%20College/field/relatig/mode/exact/conn/and/order/date McGraw Historical Society collection of New-York Central College material]\n<!--https://www.newspapers.com/image/32260714/?terms=%22central%2Bcollege%22%2Bthousand-->\n{{coord missing|New York (state)}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct universities and colleges in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Baptist universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1849]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions disestablished in 1860]]\n[[Category:Education in Cortland County, New York]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1860 disestablishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Agricultural universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Antebellum educational institutions that admitted African Americans]]\n[[Category:Recipients of aid from Gerrit Smith]]\n[[Category:American manual labor schools]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New-York_Central_College,_McGrawville"}
{"title_page": "New York University College of Arts & Science", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=November 2017}}\n<br />\n{{Infobox university\n| name = NYU College of Arts and Science\n| image = NYU CAS logo.png\n| established = 1832\n| dean = [[Gene Andrew Jarrett]]\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| parent = [[New York University]]\n| enrollment = 7,660\n| colors = Mayfair Violet<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nyu.edu/content/dam/nyu/cmsTeam/documents/NYUGraphStandards.pdf |title=New York University Graphic Standards and Logo Usage Guide, second edition, February 2010|publisher=New York University|format=PDF |access-date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> {{color box|#57068C}}\n| address = 32 Waverly Pl, New York, NY 10003\n| city = [[New York City]]\n| state = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| postalcode = 10003\n| country = U.S.\n| website = {{url|cas.nyu.edu}}\n}}[[File:Silver Center1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Silver Center for Arts and Science]]\n\nThe '''New York University College of Arts & Science''' ('''CAS''') is the primary [[liberal arts college]] of [[New York University|New York University (NYU)]]. The school is located near [[Gould Plaza]] next to the [[Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences]] and the [[New York University Stern School of Business|Stern School of Business]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://meet.nyu.edu/locations/gould-plaza/|title=Gould Plaza|website=MEET NYU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nAs the oldest and largest college within NYU, the College of Arts & Science currently enrolls 7,660 undergraduate students (as of 2017). The College of Arts & Science offers [[Bachelor of Arts]] (B.A.) and [[Bachelor of Science]] (B.S.) degrees. It is located within 2 miles of [[Washington Square Park]] in [[Greenwich Village]], which has been a hub for politics and culture in [[New York City]].\n\nSeveral departments within the College are ranked as some of the best in the world. In 2019, several Arts & Science departments were ranked in the top 10 of the [[Academic Ranking of World Universities|Academic Rankings of World Universities]] by Academic Subject including [[Economics]], [[Politics]], [[Psychology]], and [[Sociology]].<ref>http://www.shanghairanking.com/Shanghairanking-Subject-Rankings/index.html.</ref> In the 2020 [[QS World University Rankings]], NYU was ranked 1st in [[Philosophy]], 10th in [[Mathematics]], and 15th in [[English language|English Language and Literature]].<ref>https://www.topuniversities.com/node/294786/ranking-details/university-subject-rankings/--2017/philosophy</ref>\n\nAdmission to the College of Arts & Science is highly competitive with an acceptance rate of 9% for the class of 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mailchi.mp/nyu.edu/college-newsletter-spring-797625?e=cc06a0c281|title=Dean's Letter {{!}} New York University|last=Garrett|first=Gene|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nThe college provides an undergraduate liberal arts education through its Core Curriculum. Undergraduate students may select from 66 majors as well as a host of accelerated Bachelor's-Master's and pre-professional programs offered through 30 departments, many of which also offer courses at NYU's 13 study away sites. Additionally, students may select from over 60 minors offered within the College as well as 40 cross-school minors at other colleges within NYU.\n\n== Student life ==\n\n=== Clubs and traditions ===\nThe school also hosts multiple student organizations, including [[greek life]], [[Politics|political]], [[Religion|religious]], [[Ethnic group|ethnic]], and [[Musical performance|music performance]] groups (often with the [[New York University Tisch School of the Arts|Tisch School of Arts]]).\n\nThe university also sponsors some traditions for undergraduates including Apple Fest, the Violet Ball, Strawberry Festival, and the semi-annual [[midnight breakfast]] where Student Affairs administrators serve free breakfast to students before [[Final examination|finals]].\n\n=== Publications and journalism clubs ===\nThe College of Arts and Science runs several student journalism clubs and publication with the [[Arthur L. Carter Journalism Institute]], including ''[[Washington Square News]]'', ''[[NYU Local]]'', ''[[Washington Square Local]]'', and the literary journals ''[[Washington Square Review]]'' and ''[[The Minetta Review]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyulocal.com/guide-to-majors-at-nyu-journalism-a5af1aa5d37c|title=Guide To Majors At NYU: Journalism|last=Local|first=N. Y. U.|date=2016-11-16|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The university also associated (though not officially affiliated) with the campus comedy magazine, ''The Plague'', which started to pole fun at [[popular culture]] as well as campus life and the idiosyncrasies of NYU in 1978.\n\nThe university also runs a radio station [[WNYU-FM]] 89.1, which broadcasts to the entire [[New York metropolitan area]].\n\n=== Secret societies ===\nSeveral undergraduate [[Secret society|secret societies]] have existed at the College of Arts & Science. Starting in 1832, the [[Philomathean Society (New York University)|Philomathean Society]] and the [[Eucleian Society]] were formed, making rivals of each other. When the Philomathean Society died out, its remnants formed the Andiron Club in 1904.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/archives/andiron/bioghist.html|title=Guide to the Records of the Andiron Club of New York City MC 19|website=dlib.nyu.edu|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The most selective and famous club on campus is the [[Red Dragon Society]], founded in 1898, which continues to exist to this day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/test/175/pages/year.htm|title=Red Dragon Society|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Many notable NYU alumni have been members of these secret societies, including [[Elmer Ellsworth Brown]], [[Howard Cann]], [[John Harvey Kellogg]], [[Walter Reed]], and [[Frederic Tuten]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/these-10-secret-societies-are-among-higher-eds-most-mysterious/320487/|title=These 10 secret societies are among higher ed's most mysterious|website=Education Dive|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>  [[Edgar Allan Poe|Edgar Allen Poe]] famously taught at the Eucleian Society.<ref name=\":1\" /> Alumni include some of America's most prominent [[Doctor (title)|doctors]], [[Lawyer|attorneys]], [[politician]]s, [[Businessperson|business people]], [[artist]]s and wealthiest alumni of the [[New York University|College]].\n\nThere have been several attempts to restart old societies by both former and incoming undergraduate classes.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{main|List of New York University alumni|List of New York University faculty}}\n\n===Academics===\n\n[[File:Howard Zinn at lectern cropped.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Howard Zinn]], Class of 1967]]\n[[File:Martha Nussbaum wikipedia 10-10.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Martha Nussbaum]], Class of 1969]]\n* [[Edward J. Bloustein]], B.A. 1948; former president of Rutgers University, New Brunswick, New Jersey\n* [[Lionel Casson]], B.A. 1934; classicist, archeologist, professor emeritus at New York University\n* [[Howard Crosby (minister)|Howard Crosby]], B.A. 1844; Presbyterian minister and NYU chancellor 1870\u20131881\n* [[Richard Davidson]], B.A. 1972; Professor of Psychology at [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n* [[Morris Janowitz]], B.A. 1941; founder of [[military sociology]], professor at [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Richard Joel]], B.A. 1972; current president of [[Yeshiva University]], New York City\n* [[Joseph Keller]], B.A. 1943; 1988 [[National Medal of Science]] recipient\n* [[Paul Kurtz]], B.A. 1948; Professor Emeritus of Philosophy at the [[State University of New York at Buffalo]]\n* [[Ellen Langer]], B.A. 1970; Professor of Psychology at [[Harvard University]]\n* [[Peter D. Lax]], B.A. 1947; mathematician, 2005 [[Abel Prize]] recipient, 1986 [[National Medal of Science]] recipient\n* [[Sherwin B. Nuland]], B.A. 1951; bioethicist, author of ''How We Die''\n* [[Martha Nussbaum]], B.A. 1969; philosopher, professor at [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Leonard Peikoff]], B.A. 1954; philosopher, leading advocate of [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivism]]\n* [[Howard Zinn]], B.A. 1951; historian, author of ''[[A People's History of the United States]]''\n\n===Arts, acting, and entertainment===\n\n* [[Milton Babbitt]], B.A. 1935; composer, 1986 [[MacArthur Fellow]]\n* [[Bob Balaban]], B.A. 1977; actor\n* [[Neil Diamond]] (Did not graduate); musician\n* [[Tom Ford]] (Did not graduate); fashion designer and film director\n* [[William Gaines]], B.A. 1948; founder of [[MAD Magazine]]\n* [[Ilana Glazer]], B.A. 2009; co-star and co-creator of the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Broad City]]''\n* [[Ethan Hawke]] (Did not graduate); actor\n* [[Tom Kirdahy]], B.A. 1985; Theater producer and activist\n* [[Stanley Kramer]], B.A. 1933; film director\n* [[Ken Leung]], B.A. 1992; actor\n* [[Dave Liebman]], B.A. 1967; jazz musician\n* [[Leonard Maltin]], B.A. 1973; film critic\n* [[Glen Mazzara]], B.A. 1989; television producer\n* [[Alan Menken]], B.A. 1972; musical theater and film composer\n* [[Meg Ryan]], B.A. 1982; actor\n[[File:Martin Scorsese Berlinale 2010 (cropped).jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Martin Scorsese]], Class of 1964]]\n* [[Martin Scorsese]], B.A; 1964; film director, 2006 recipient of [[Academy Award for Best Director]]\n\n===Authors and writers===\n[[File:Frank mccourt 20060912.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Frank McCourt]], Class of 1957]]\n* [[Warren Adler]], B.A. 1947; author of ''[[The War of the Roses (novel)|The War of the Roses]]''\n* [[Caleb Carr]], B.A. 1977; author\n[[File:Elizabeth Gilbert at TED.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Elizabeth Gilbert]], Class of 1991]]\n* [[Elizabeth Gilbert]], B.A. 1991; author of ''[[Eat, Pray, Love]]''\n* [[Joseph Heller]], B.A. 1948; author of ''[[Catch-22]]''\n* [[Ira Levin]], B.A. 1950; author\n* [[Frank McCourt]], B.A. 1957; 1997 [[Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography]] recipient, author of ''[[Angela's Ashes]]''\n* [[Cynthia Ozick]], B.A. 1930; author\n* [[Kira Peikoff]], B.A. 2007; author and journalist\n* [[Charles Simic]], B.A. 1967; 1984 [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellow]], Recipient of 1990 [[Pulitzer Prize for Poetry]], 15th [[Poet Laureate Consultant in Poetry to the Library of Congress|United States Poet Laureate]]\n\n===Business===\n\n[[File:Maria Bartiromo.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Maria Bartiromo]], Class of 1987]]\n* [[Maria Bartiromo]], B.A. 1987; [[Fox Business Network]] television journalist\n* [[Clive Davis]], B.A. 1953; founder of [[Arista Records]]\n* [[Marvin Davis]], B.S. 1947; owner of [[Denver Broncos]], billionaire, industrialist\n* [[Jack Dorsey]] (Did not graduate); co-founder of [[Twitter]] and [[Square, Inc.]]\n* [[Arthur Frommer]], B.A. 1950; tourism industry writer\n* [[Scott Harrison (charity founder)|Scott Harrison]], B.A. 1998; founder and CEO of the non-profit [[charity: water]]\n* [[Boris Jordan]], B.A. 1988; billionaire, investor\n* [[Henry Kaufman]], B.A. 1948; president of Henry Kaufman & Company, Inc.\n* [[Mildred Robbins Leet]], B.A. 1942; entrepreneur and philanthropist\n* [[Mark Leslie (entrepreneur)|Mark Leslie]], B.A. 1966; venture capitalist and founder of [[Veritas Technologies]]\n* [[Joseph Nacchio]], B.S. 1970; former chairman and chief executive officer of [[Qwest|Qwest Communications International]]\n* [[Marc Rich]] (Did not graduate); commodities trader, billionaire, fugitive \n* [[Larry Silverstein]], B.A. 1952; billionaire, real estate investor\n* [[Sy Syms]], B.A. 1946; founder of Syms Clothing\n* [[Dennis Tito]], B.A. 1962; entrepreneur, [[space tourist]]\n\n===Journalism===\n\n[[File:Ray Suarez.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Ray Suarez]], Class of 1985]]\n* [[Lynda Baquero]], B.A. 1974; correspondent for [[WNBC]]\n* [[Don Hewitt]], B.A. 1941; television producer, creator of ''[[60 Minutes]]''\n* [[Ray Suarez]], B.A. 1985; broadcast journalist, host of [[Inside Story (TV programme)|Inside Story]] on [[Al Jazeera America]]\n* [[Alvin Toffler]], B.A. 1949; [[futurist]], writer, journalist\n* [[Gene Weingarten]], B.A. 1973; ''[[Washington Post]]'' journalist, two-time [[Pulitzer Prize]] winner\n\n===Law===\n\n* [[Constance Baker Motley]], B.A. 1940; civil rights activist, judge, state senator, [[Borough President]] of [[Manhattan]]\n* [[Evan Chesler]], B.A. 1970; partner and chairman, [[Cravath, Swaine & Moore]]\n* [[Jonathan Lippman]], B.A. 1965; [[Chief Judge of the New York Court of Appeals]]\n* [[Victor Marrero]], B.A. 1963; United States federal senior judge\n* [[Herbert Wachtell]], B.S. 1952; co-founder of the law firm of [[Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz]].\n\n===Politics and government===\n* [[Jerome Anthony Ambro]], B.A. 1955; US Congressman\n* [[Bill de Blasio]], B.A. 1984; 109th [[Mayor of New York City]]\n* [[Irwin Delmore Davidson]], B.S. 1927; US Congressman\n* [[Thomas De Witt Talmage]], B.A. 1853; preacher, religious leader, social reformer\n* [[Steven Boghos Derounian]], B.A. 1938; US Congressman\n* [[William Henry Draper, Jr.]], B.A. 1916; first [[United States Permanent Representative to NATO|U.S. Permanent Representative to NATO]]\n* [[Fernando Ferrer]], B.A. 1972; former Bronx Borough president and 2005 Democratic nominee for Mayor of New York\n* [[Henry Grunwald (editor)|Henry Grunwald]], B.A. 1944; U.S. ambassador; former managing editor of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine and [[editor in chief]] of [[Time, Inc.]] \n* [[Sean Hannity]] (did not graduate); political commentator\n* [[Frank L. Howley]], B.S. 1925; brigadier general, commandant of the American sector of Berlin\n* [[Jacob Javits]], B.A. 1923; US Senator from New York from 1957 to 1981\n* [[Samuel Levy]], B.A. 1894; Manhattan Borough President\n* [[Martha Roby]], B.A. 1998; US Congresswoman\n* [[Albert del Rosario]], B.S. 1960; former Philippine ambassador to the US. Currently the Philippine Foreign Affairs Secretary\n[[File:Howard cosell 1975.JPG|thumb|alt=|[[Howard Cosell]], Class of 1938]]\n'''Science and technology:'''\n* [[Balamurali Ambati]], B.A. 1991; youngest person ever to become a physician\n* [[Evelyn Berezin]], B.S. 1951; computer engineer\n* [[Eugene Braunwald]], B.A. 1949; cardiologist\n* [[Humayun Chaudhry]], B.A., 1986; president and CEO, [[Federation of State Medical Boards]]\n* [[Avery Fisher]], B.S. 1929; inventor of the [[transistorized]] [[Electronic amplifier|amplifier]] and the first [[stereophonic sound|stereo]] [[radio]]-[[phonograph]], noted [[philanthropist]]\n* [[Neil Garg]], B.S. 2000; Professor of Chemistry at [[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Chris Harrison (computer scientist)|Chris Harrison]], B.S. 2005; computer scientist and entrepreneur, assistant professor at [[Carnegie Mellon University]]\n* [[Henry Sherwood Lawrence]], B.A. 1938; immunologist\n* [[Alfred Vail]], B.A. 1836; inventor\n* [[George Wald]], B.A. 1927; recipient of 1967 [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]]\n\n===Sports===\n\n* [[Marv Albert]], B.A. 1965; sportscaster\n* [[Howard Cann]], B.A. 1920; 1968 Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame Inductee\n* [[Howard Cosell]], B.A. 1938; sportscaster\n* [[Carol Heiss]], B.A. 1961; gold medal winner, Olympic Winter Games 1960\n* [[Mika'il Sankofa]], B.A. 1988; fencer, Olympic Gold Medalist\n* [[Dolph Schayes]], B.S. 1948, [[List of NBA champions|NBA champion]] ([[1955 NBA Finals|1955]]), 12\u00d7 [[List of NBA All-Stars|NBA All-Star]], [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] Inductee\n* [[Ed Smith (American football)|Ed Smith]], B.A. 1934; model for [[Heisman Trophy]]\n* [[George Spitz]], B.A. 1934; world record high jumper\n* [[Colin Cassady]], B.S.; WWE wrestler\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official Website|http://www.cas.nyu.edu}}\n* [http://www.nyu.edu/admissions.html Admission information]\n* [http://www.nyu.edu/academics.html Academics]\n* [http://www.nyu.edu/research.html Research]\n\n{{New York University}}\n\n{{coord|40.73023|N|73.99569|W|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New York University College of Arts and Science}}\n[[Category:New York University schools|Arts and Science]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1832]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges at universities in the United States]]\n[[Category:1832 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "<br />{{Advert|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = NYU College of Arts and Science\n| image = NYU CAS logo.png\n| established = 1832\n| dean = [[Gene Andrew Jarrett]]\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| parent = [[New York University]]\n| enrollment = 7,660\n| colors = Mayfair Violet<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nyu.edu/content/dam/nyu/cmsTeam/documents/NYUGraphStandards.pdf |title=New York University Graphic Standards and Logo Usage Guide, second edition, February 2010|publisher=New York University|format=PDF |access-date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> {{color box|#57068C}}\n| address = 32 Waverly Pl, New York, NY 10003\n| city = [[New York City]]\n| state = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| postalcode = 10003\n| country = U.S.\n| website = {{url|cas.nyu.edu}}\n}}[[File:Silver Center1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Silver Center for Arts and Science]]\n\nThe '''New York University College of Arts & Science''' ('''CAS''') is the primary [[liberal arts college]] of [[New York University|New York University (NYU)]]. The school is located near [[Gould Plaza]] next to the [[Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences]] and the [[New York University Stern School of Business|Stern School of Business]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://meet.nyu.edu/locations/gould-plaza/|title=Gould Plaza|website=MEET NYU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> \n\nAs the oldest and largest college within NYU, the College of Arts & Science currently enrolls 7,660 undergraduate students (as of 2017). The College of Arts & Science offers [[Bachelor of Arts]] (B.A.) and [[Bachelor of Science]] (B.S.) degrees. It is located within 2 miles of [[Washington Square Park]] in [[Greenwich Village]], which has been a hub for politics and culture in [[New York City]]. \n\nSeveral departments within the College are ranked as some of the best in the world. In 2019, several Arts & Science departments were ranked in the top 10 of the [[Academic Ranking of World Universities|Academic Rankings of World Universities]] by Academic Subject including [[Economics]], [[Politics]], [[Psychology]], and [[Sociology]].<ref>http://www.shanghairanking.com/Shanghairanking-Subject-Rankings/index.html.</ref> In the 2020 [[QS World University Rankings|QS World University Rankings]], NYU was ranked 1st in [[Philosophy]], 10th in [[Mathematics]], and 15th in [[English language|English Language and Literature]].<ref>https://www.topuniversities.com/node/294786/ranking-details/university-subject-rankings/--2017/philosophy</ref>\n\nAdmission to the College of Arts & Science is highly competitive with an acceptance rate of 9% for the class of 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mailchi.mp/nyu.edu/college-newsletter-spring-797625?e=cc06a0c281|title=Dean's Letter {{!}} New York University|last=Garrett|first=Gene|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\n==Academics==\nThe college provides an undergraduate liberal arts education through its Core Curriculum. Undergraduate students may select from 66 majors as well as a host of accelerated Bachelor's-Master's and pre-professional programs offered through 30 departments, many of which also offer courses at NYU's 13 study away sites. Additionally, students may select from over 60 minors offered within the College as well as 40 cross-school minors at other colleges within NYU.\n\n== Student life ==\n\n=== Clubs and traditions ===\nThe school also hosts multiple student organizations, including [[greek life]], [[Politics|political]], [[Religion|religious]], [[Ethnic group|ethnic]], and [[Musical performance|music performance]] groups (often with the [[New York University Tisch School of the Arts|Tisch School of Arts]]). \n\nThe university also sponsors some traditions for undergraduates including Apple Fest, the Violet Ball, Strawberry Festival, and the semi-annual [[midnight breakfast]] where Student Affairs administrators serve free breakfast to students before [[Final examination|finals]].\n\n=== Publications and journalism clubs ===\nThe College of Arts and Science runs several student journalism clubs and publication with the [[Arthur L. Carter Journalism Institute]], including [[Washington Square News|''Washington Square News'']], ''[[NYU Local]]'', ''[[Washington Square Local]]'', and the literary journals ''[[Washington Square Review]]'' and ''[[The Minetta Review]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyulocal.com/guide-to-majors-at-nyu-journalism-a5af1aa5d37c|title=Guide To Majors At NYU: Journalism|last=Local|first=N. Y. U.|date=2016-11-16|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The university also associated (though not officially affiliated) with the campus comedy magazine, ''The Plague'', which started to pole fun at [[popular culture]] as well as campus life and the idiosyncrasies of NYU in 1978.\n\nThe university also runs a radio station [[WNYU-FM]] 89.1, which broadcasts to the entire [[New York metropolitan area]]. \n\n=== Secret societies ===\nSeveral undergraduate [[Secret society|secret societies]] have existed at the College of Arts & Science. Starting in 1832, the [[Philomathean Society (New York University)|Philomathean Society]] and the [[Eucleian Society]] were formed, making rivals of each other. When the Philomathean Society died out, its remnants formed the Andiron Club in 1904.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/archives/andiron/bioghist.html|title=Guide to the Records of the Andiron Club of New York City MC 19|website=dlib.nyu.edu|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The most selective and famous club on campus is the [[Red Dragon Society]], founded in 1898, which continues to exist to this day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/test/175/pages/year.htm|title=Red Dragon Society|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Many notable NYU alumni have been members of these secret societies, including [[Elmer Ellsworth Brown]], [[Howard Cann]], [[John Harvey Kellogg]], [[Walter Reed]], and [[Frederic Tuten]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/these-10-secret-societies-are-among-higher-eds-most-mysterious/320487/|title=These 10 secret societies are among higher ed's most mysterious|website=Education Dive|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>  [[Edgar Allan Poe|Edgar Allen Poe]] famously taught at the Eucleian Society.<ref name=\":1\" /> Alumni include some of America's most prominent [[Doctor (title)|doctors]], [[Lawyer|attorneys]], [[Politician|politicians]], [[Businessperson|business people]], [[Artist|artists]] and wealthiest alumni of the [[New York University|College]].  \n\nThere have been several attempts to restart old societies by both former and incoming undergraduate classes. \n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{main|List of New York University alumni|List of New York University faculty}}\n\n===Academics===\n\n[[File:Howard Zinn at lectern cropped.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Howard Zinn]], Class of 1967]]\n[[File:Martha Nussbaum wikipedia 10-10.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Martha Nussbaum]], Class of 1969]]\n* [[Edward J. Bloustein]], B.A. 1948; former president of Rutgers University, New Brunswick, New Jersey\n* [[Lionel Casson]], B.A. 1934; classicist, archeologist, professor emeritus at New York University\n* [[Howard Crosby (minister)|Howard Crosby]], B.A. 1844; Presbyterian minister and NYU chancellor 1870\u20131881\n* [[Richard Davidson]], B.A. 1972; Professor of Psychology at [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n* [[Morris Janowitz]], B.A. 1941; founder of [[military sociology]], professor at [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Richard Joel]], B.A. 1972; current president of [[Yeshiva University]], New York City\n* [[Joseph Keller]], B.A. 1943; 1988 [[National Medal of Science]] recipient\n* [[Paul Kurtz]], B.A. 1948; Professor Emeritus of Philosophy at the [[State University of New York at Buffalo]]\n* [[Ellen Langer]], B.A. 1970; Professor of Psychology at [[Harvard University]]\n* [[Peter D. Lax]], B.A. 1947; mathematician, 2005 [[Abel Prize]] recipient, 1986 [[National Medal of Science]] recipient\n* [[Sherwin B. Nuland]], B.A. 1951; bioethicist, author of ''How We Die''\n* [[Martha Nussbaum]], B.A. 1969; philosopher, professor at [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Leonard Peikoff]], B.A. 1954; philosopher, leading advocate of [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivism]]\n* [[Howard Zinn]], B.A. 1951; historian, author of ''[[A People's History of the United States]]''\n\n===Arts, acting, and entertainment===\n\n* [[Milton Babbitt]], B.A. 1935; composer, 1986 [[MacArthur Fellow]]\n* [[Bob Balaban]], B.A. 1977; actor\n* [[Neil Diamond]] (Did not graduate); musician\n* [[Tom Ford]] (Did not graduate); fashion designer and film director\n* [[William Gaines]], B.A. 1948; founder of [[MAD Magazine]]\n* [[Ilana Glazer]], B.A. 2009; co-star and co-creator of the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Broad City]]''\n* [[Ethan Hawke]] (Did not graduate); actor\n* [[Tom Kirdahy]], B.A. 1985; Theater producer and activist\n* [[Stanley Kramer]], B.A. 1933; film director\n* [[Ken Leung]], B.A. 1992; actor\n* [[Dave Liebman]], B.A. 1967; jazz musician\n* [[Leonard Maltin]], B.A. 1973; film critic\n* [[Glen Mazzara]], B.A. 1989; television producer\n* [[Alan Menken]], B.A. 1972; musical theater and film composer\n* [[Meg Ryan]], B.A. 1982; actor\n[[File:Martin Scorsese Berlinale 2010 (cropped).jpg|