egory:Liberal arts colleges in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1887]]\n[[Category:Education in Lincoln, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Members of the Annapolis Group]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lincoln, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in Nebraska]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nebraska_Wesleyan_University"}
{"title_page": "NYU Liberal Studies", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = NYU Liberal Studies\n| image = New York University Arts & Science Liberal Studies.png\n| established = 2009\n| dean = [[Julie Mostov]]\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| parent = [[New York University]]\n| colors = Mayfair Violet<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nyu.edu/content/dam/nyu/cmsTeam/documents/NYUGraphStandards.pdf |title=New York University Graphic Standards and Logo Usage Guide, second edition, February 2010|publisher=New York University|format=PDF |access-date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> {{color box|#57068C}}\n| city = [[New York City]]\n| state = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| country = [[United States of America]]\n| website = {{url|www.liberalstudies.nyu.edu}}\n}}\n'''Liberal Studies''' is a school in the Faculty of Arts and Science at [[New York University]]. It houses the Liberal Studies Core Program and the Global Liberal Studies [[bachelor's degree]] program.<ref name=\"asu.edu\">{{Cite web |url=https://universitydesign.asu.edu/db/nyu-freshmen-abroad-programs |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402164528/https://universitydesign.asu.edu/db/nyu-freshmen-abroad-programs |archive-date=2016-04-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Both of the department's programs employ a [[Curriculum#Core curriculum|core curriculum]] in the [[liberal arts]] and emphasize [[Study abroad|global study]] in NYU's Global Network University framework.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/22/education/edlife/general-studies-moves-to-the-mainstream.html|title=General Studies Moves to the Mainstream|first=Eric|last=Platt|date=13 February 2018|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Liberal Studies Core Program==\nThe Liberal Studies Core Program is a two-year [[liberal arts]] academic program centered on the [[great books]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/12/26/nyregion/the-added-option-of-general-studies.html|title=The Added Option Of General Studies|first=Samuel|last=Weiss|date=26 December 2001|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> First-year students study at NYU's campuses in [[New York University|New York City]], [[NYU London|London]], [[NYU Paris|Paris]], Washington D.C., or [[NYU Florence|Florence]]. After the second year, students transfer to take up residence in one of NYU's other degree-granting colleges.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/11/education/11accept.html|title=Admission to College, but a Wait of a Year|first=Lisa W.|last=Foderaro|date=10 April 2011|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Global Liberal Studies==\nGlobal Liberal Studies is a four-year [[bachelor's degree]] program.<ref name=\"asu.edu\"/> First-year students study at NYU's campuses in [[New York University|New York City]], [[NYU London|London]], [[NYU Paris|Paris]], and [[NYU Florence|Florence]], before moving to New York City for the sophomore year. Third-year students are required to study at one of NYU's fourteen global academic centers.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{New York University}}\n\n{{coord|40.729232|-73.993278|type:edu_region:US-NY|display=inline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:New York University schools|Liberal Studies]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges at universities in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = NYU Liberal Studies\n| image = New York University Arts & Science Liberal Studies.png\n| established = 2009\n| dean = [[Julie Mostov]]\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| parent = [[New York University]]\n| colors = Mayfair Violet<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nyu.edu/content/dam/nyu/cmsTeam/documents/NYUGraphStandards.pdf |title=New York University Graphic Standards and Logo Usage Guide, second edition, February 2010|publisher=New York University|format=PDF |access-date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> {{color box|#57068C}}\n| city = [[New York City]]\n| state = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| country = [[United States of America]]\n| website = {{url|www.liberalstudies.nyu.edu}}\n}}\n'''Liberal Studies''' is a school in the Faculty of Arts and Science at [[New York University]]. It houses the Liberal Studies Core Program and the Global Liberal Studies [[bachelor's degree]] program.<ref name=\"asu.edu\">{{Cite web |url=https://universitydesign.asu.edu/db/nyu-freshmen-abroad-programs |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402164528/https://universitydesign.asu.edu/db/nyu-freshmen-abroad-programs |archive-date=2016-04-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Both of the department's programs employ a [[Curriculum#Core curriculum|core curriculum]] in the [[liberal arts]] and emphasize [[Study abroad|global study]] in NYU's Global Network University framework.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/22/education/edlife/general-studies-moves-to-the-mainstream.html|title=General Studies Moves to the Mainstream|first=Eric|last=Platt|date=13 February 2018|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Liberal Studies Core Program==\nThe Liberal Studies Core Program is a two-year [[liberal arts]] academic program centered on the [[great books]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/12/26/nyregion/the-added-option-of-general-studies.html|title=The Added Option Of General Studies|first=Samuel|last=Weiss|date=26 December 2001|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> First-year students study at NYU's campuses in [[New York University|New York City]], [[NYU London|London]], [[NYU Paris|Paris]], Washington D.C., or [[NYU Florence|Florence]]. After the second year, students transfer to take up residence in one of NYU's other degree-granting colleges.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/11/education/11accept.html|title=Admission to College, but a Wait of a Year|first=Lisa W.|last=Foderaro|date=10 April 2011|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Global Liberal Studies==\nGlobal Liberal Studies is a four-year [[bachelor's degree]] program.<ref name=\"asu.edu\"/> First-year students study at NYU's campuses in [[New York University|New York City]], [[NYU London|London]], [[NYU Paris|Paris]], and [[NYU Florence|Florence]], before moving to New York City for the sophomore year. Third-year students are required to study at one of NYU's fourteen global academic centers.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{New York University}}\n\n{{coord|40.729232|-73.993278|type:edu_region:US-NY|display=inline}}\n\n[[Category:New York University schools|Liberal Studies]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges at universities in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NYU_Liberal_Studies"}
{"title_page": "Mount Mercy University", "text_new": "{{short description|American Catholic liberal arts university}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name                  = Mount Mercy University\n| image_name            = 2012-0610-MtMercyCollege02.jpg\n| image_size            = \n| caption               = Warde Hall\n| established           = 1928\n| president             = Laurie Hamen\n| type                  = [[Private school|Private]]\n| religious_affiliation = [[Roman Catholic]] <br> ([[Sisters of Mercy]])\n| endowment             = $23.6 million<ref>As of June 30, 2010. {{Cite web | title = U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2009 Endowment Market Value and Percentage Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2009 to FY 2010 | work = 2009 NACUBO-Commonfund Study of Endowments | publisher = National Association of College and University Business Officers | url = http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/research/2010_NCSE_Public_Tables_Endowment_Market_Values.pdf | format = PDF }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| city                  = [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa|Cedar Rapids]]\n| state                 = [[Iowa]]\n| country               = United States\n| enrollment            = 1,824 (1,115 full-time)\n| campus                = [[Urban area|Urban]], 40 acres\n| athletics             = [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]] \u2013 [[Heart of America Athletic Conference|HAAC]]\n| nickname              = Mustangs\n| mascot                = Mustang Sally\n| colors         = Blue and gold\n| logo                = Emblem.jpg\n| website               = {{url|www.mtmercy.edu}}\n| affiliations          = [[Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities|ACCU]]<br>[[Council of Independent Colleges|CIC]]<br>[[National Association of Independent Colleges and Universities|NAICU]]\n| motto               = Pacem et Veritatem Diligite\n}}\n'''Mount Mercy University''' is a [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] [[liberal arts university]] in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]]. The school was founded by the [[Sisters of Mercy]] in 1928.\n\nStudents take a core of liberal arts courses providing a comprehensive foundation for many specific areas of study including: English, fine arts, history, mathematics, multicultural studies, natural science, philosophy, religious studies, social science and speech/drama. The university offers more than 45 undergraduate programs of study and six graduate programs. A number of these programs are available for online learning.\n\n==Campus==\nMount Mercy University's 40-acre campus is located in a tree-lined residential neighborhood in the heart of [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]] (population 126,326). The [[Our Mother of Sorrows Grotto Historic District|Our Mother of Sorrows Grotto]] is listed as a [[Historic districts in the United States|historic district]] on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=Miller>{{cite news |url=http://www.thegazette.com/mount-mercy-grotto-makes-national-register-20150430|title=Mount Mercy grotto makes National Register |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Cedar Rapids)|The Gazette]]|location=Cedar Rapids|date=April 30, 2015|accessdate=2017-09-14|author=Vanessa Miller}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMount Mercy University was founded as a two-year college for women in 1928 by the Sisters of Mercy of Cedar Rapids, Iowa. These [[Religious sister|sisters]], whose order was founded in 1831 by Catherine McAuley in Dublin, Ireland, have been active in Cedar Rapids since 1875. The college was an outgrowth of their concerns about the education of women.\n\nIn 1957, Mount Mercy became a four-year institution and awarded its first bachelor's degree in 1959. The college received accreditation as a baccalaureate institution by the North Central Association in 1960. In 1968 the Sisters of Mercy transferred their legal authority and responsibility to a self-perpetuating independent board of which three members would always be Sisters of Mercy.  Mount Mercy College became coeducational in 1969. While integrating a strong liberal arts component, the college has always emphasized professional development from its early involvement, as a junior college, on business courses and teacher education. The departments of nursing, education, and social work were accredited in the 1960s and 1970s as the four-year programs developed. Begun in 1997, the Adult Accelerated program, a joint Mount Mercy University/Kirkwood Community College accelerated degree completion program for working adults meets an important community workforce development need.\n\nOn August 23, 2010, the institution was re-designated as a university.\n\n===Presidents===\n*Sister Mary Ildephonse Holland, 1928\u20131933, 1946\u20131961\n*Sister Mary Cornelia Burke, 1933 to 1939\n*Sister Mary Maura Marron, 1939\u20131946\n*Sister Mary Agnes Hennessey, 1961\u20131977\n*Dr. Thomas R. Feld, 1977\u20131999\n*Dr. Robert Pearce, 1999\u20132006\n*Dr. Christopher R.L. Blake, 2006\u20132013<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20100527111750/http://www.mtmercy.edu/offices/presidents_office/meet-the-president.html</ref>\n*Dr. Laurie Hamen, 2014\u2013present\n\n==Catholic identity==\n\nMount Mercy is sponsored by the Institute of the Sisters of Mercy of the Americas, through the Conference for Mercy Higher Education, teaching the Sisters\u2019 five Critical Concerns\u2014 earth, immigration, nonviolence, racism, and women\u2014within an educational setting that reaches far beyond the classroom.\n\nThe university community strives to educate within the Catholic intellectual tradition, welcoming all people to explore truth, wisdom, faith, and reason. Through service learning and volunteer opportunities, students are challenged to take what they learn in the classroom and address the Critical Concerns in a wide array of projects that benefit their community and the world around them. \nThe Campus Ministry team supports students\u2019 faith development and spiritual life through daily mass, retreats, service-learning opportunities, and vocation discernment activities.\n\n===Mission===\nMount Mercy is a Catholic university that provides student-focused education in the spirit of the Sisters of Mercy and welcomes people of all beliefs to join our community in pursuit of undergraduate and graduate education and compassionate service to those in need.\n\n\u201cWe strive for excellence in accomplishing our mission through four interdependent goals: using reflective judgment, engaging in strategic communication, serving the common good, and promoting purposeful living.\u201d\n\n===Institution Values===\n\n*Lifelong learning and education of the whole person  \n*Pursuit of truth and dignity  \n*Commitment to students  \n*Justice  \n*Gratitude  \n*Hospitality  \n*Service\n\n==Institutional Awards==\n\n*Named a 2019\u201320 College of Distinction based on engaged students, great teaching, vibrant communities, and successful outcomes  \n*Named a 2020 Top 50 Best Regional Midwest University, Top 50 Best Value School, Top 50 Best College for Veterans, and Top 25 Performer on Social Mobility by U.S. News & World Report  \n*Nationally ranked student Enactus team\u2014using entrepreneurial action to transform lives and shape a better, more sustainable world  \n*Award-winning volunteerism and service-learning programs\n\n==Academics==\n\nMount Mercy offers more than 85 areas of study, organized into eight academic departments - serving traditional residential, transfer, and working adult students.\n\n===Undergraduate Programs===\n\n* Business\n* Communication, Literature & Arts\n* Education\n* History, Politics & Justice\n* Natural & Applied Sciences\n* Nursing\n* Philosophy & Religious Studies\n* Psychology, Sociology, Social Work & International Studies\n\n===Graduate and Doctorate Programs===\n\n* Master of Arts in Criminal Justice (MACJ)\n* Master of Arts in Education (MAEd)\n* Master of Arts in Marriage & Family Therapy (MFT)\n* Master of Business Administration (MBA)\n* Master of Science in Nursing (MSN)\n* Master of Strategic Leadership (MSL)\n* Doctor of Nursing Practice (DNP)\n* Doctor of Philosophy in Marriage & Family Therapy (PhD in MFT)\n\n===Online Programs===\n\n* Applied Management \n* Business \n* Human Resource Management  \n* Marketing \n* Health Care Administration \n* RN to BSN \n* Religious Studies \n* Master of Arts in Criminal Justice Master of Business Administration\n\n==Athletics==\nMount Mercy teams are known as the Mustangs. The university is a member of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] (NAIA) Division I, competing in the [[Heart of America Athletic Conference]] (HAAC). Men's sports include baseball, basketball, bowling, cross country, golf, soccer, track & field, and volleyball; while women's sports include basketball, bowling, cross country, golf, soccer, softball, track & field and volleyball. Varsity and Junior Varsity programs are available in several sports.\n[[wikt:intramural|Intramural]] activities include basketball, volleyball, golf, flag football, softball and cross country.\n\n38% of traditional undergrads are student-athletes. Mount Mercy's faculty and staff mentor program promotes success in the classroom and on the playing field .\n\n===Athletic Achievements===\n\nMount Mercy's 18 athletic teams have won 50 conference team titles and qualified for 40+ national events.\nOver 120 students have been named NAIA Scholar-Athletes in the past three years, including a record 67 in the 2018\u201319 academic year. \nIn 2018\u201319: Two NAIA national team qualifiers, 14 individual qualifiers, eight NAIA all-Americans, 67 Daktronics-NAIA Scholar-Athletes, 116 all-conference performers\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.mountmercymustangs.com/ Mount Mercy Athletics website]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Colleges and universities in Iowa}}\n{{Heart of America Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Dubuque}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Dubuque}}\n{{Women's Colleges that are Coeducational}}\n{{Conference for Mercy Higher Education}}\n}}\n{{coord|42|0|8.08|N|91|39|5.49|W|type:edu_region:US|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Mount Mercy University| ]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Education in Cedar Rapids, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1928]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Dubuque]]\n[[Category:Education in Linn County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cedar Rapids, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cedar Rapids, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Former women's universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sisters of Mercy colleges and universities]]\n[[Category:Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American Catholic liberal arts university}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name                  = Mount Mercy University\n| image_name            = 2012-0610-MtMercyCollege02.jpg\n| image_size            = \n| caption               = Warde Hall\n| established           = 1928\n| president             = Laurie Hamen\n| type                  = [[Private school|Private]]\n| religious_affiliation = [[Roman Catholic]] <br> ([[Sisters of Mercy]])\n| endowment             = $23.6 million<ref>As of June 30, 2010. {{Cite web | title = U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2009 Endowment Market Value and Percentage Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2009 to FY 2010 | work = 2009 NACUBO-Commonfund Study of Endowments | publisher = National Association of College and University Business Officers | url = http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/research/2010_NCSE_Public_Tables_Endowment_Market_Values.pdf | format = PDF }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| city                  = [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa|Cedar Rapids]]\n| state                 = [[Iowa]]\n| country               = United States\n| enrollment            = 1,824 (1,115 full-time)\n| campus                = [[Urban area|Urban]], 40 acres\n| athletics             = [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]] \u2013 [[Heart of America Athletic Conference|HAAC]]\n| nickname              = Mustangs\n| mascot                = Mustang Sally\n| colors         = Blue and gold\n| logo                = Emblem.jpg\n| website               = {{url|www.mtmercy.edu}}\n| affiliations          = [[Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities|ACCU]]<br>[[Council of Independent Colleges|CIC]]<br>[[National Association of Independent Colleges and Universities|NAICU]]\n| motto               = Pacem et Veritatem Diligite\n}}\n'''Mount Mercy University''' is a [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] [[liberal arts university]] in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]]. The school was founded by the [[Sisters of Mercy]] in 1928.\n\nStudents take a core of liberal arts courses providing a comprehensive foundation for many specific areas of study including: English, fine arts, history, mathematics, multicultural studies, natural science, philosophy, religious studies, social science and speech/drama. The university offers more than 45 undergraduate programs of study and six graduate programs. A number of these programs are available for online learning.\n\n==Campus==\nMount Mercy University's 40-acre campus is located in a tree-lined residential neighborhood in the heart of [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]] (population 126,326). The [[Our Mother of Sorrows Grotto Historic District|Our Mother of Sorrows Grotto]] is listed as a [[Historic districts in the United States|historic district]] on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=Miller>{{cite news |url=http://www.thegazette.com/mount-mercy-grotto-makes-national-register-20150430|title=Mount Mercy grotto makes National Register |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Cedar Rapids)|The Gazette]]|location=Cedar Rapids|date=April 30, 2015|accessdate=2017-09-14|author=Vanessa Miller}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMount Mercy University was founded as a two-year college for women in 1928 by the Sisters of Mercy of Cedar Rapids, Iowa. These [[Religious sister|sisters]], whose order was founded in 1831 by Catherine McAuley in Dublin, Ireland, have been active in Cedar Rapids since 1875. The college was an outgrowth of their concerns about the education of women.\n\nIn 1957, Mount Mercy became a four-year institution and awarded its first bachelor's degree in 1959. The college received accreditation as a baccalaureate institution by the North Central Association in 1960. In 1968 the Sisters of Mercy transferred their legal authority and responsibility to a self-perpetuating independent board of which three members would always be Sisters of Mercy.  Mount Mercy College became coeducational in 1969. While integrating a strong liberal arts component, the college has always emphasized professional development from its early involvement, as a junior college, on business courses and teacher education. The departments of nursing, education, and social work were accredited in the 1960s and 1970s as the four-year programs developed. Begun in 1997, the Adult Accelerated program, a joint Mount Mercy University/Kirkwood Community College accelerated degree completion program for working adults meets an important community workforce development need.\n\nOn August 23, 2010, the institution was re-designated as a university.\n\n===Presidents===\n*Sister Mary Ildephonse Holland, 1928\u20131933, 1946\u20131961\n*Sister Mary Cornelia Burke, 1933 to 1939\n*Sister Mary Maura Marron, 1939\u20131946\n*Sister Mary Agnes Hennessey, 1961\u20131977\n*Dr. Thomas R. Feld, 1977\u20131999\n*Dr. Robert Pearce, 1999\u20132006\n*Dr. Christopher R.L. Blake, 2006\u20132013<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20100527111750/http://www.mtmercy.edu/offices/presidents_office/meet-the-president.html</ref>\n*Dr. Laurie Hamen, 2014\u2013present\n\n==Catholic identity==\n\nMount Mercy is sponsored by the Institute of the Sisters of Mercy of the Americas, through the Conference for Mercy Higher Education, teaching the Sisters\u2019 five Critical Concerns\u2014 earth, immigration, nonviolence, racism, and women\u2014within an educational setting that reaches far beyond the classroom.\n\nThe university community strives to educate within the Catholic intellectual tradition, welcoming all people to explore truth, wisdom, faith, and reason. Through service learning and volunteer opportunities, students are challenged to take what they learn in the classroom and address the Critical Concerns in a wide array of projects that benefit their community and the world around them. \nThe Campus Ministry team supports students\u2019 faith development and spiritual life through daily mass, retreats, service-learning opportunities, and vocation discernment activities.\n\n===Mission===\nMount Mercy is a Catholic university that provides student-focused education in the spirit of the Sisters of Mercy and welcomes people of all beliefs to join our community in pursuit of undergraduate and graduate education and compassionate service to those in need.\n\n\u201cWe strive for excellence in accomplishing our mission through four interdependent goals: using reflective judgment, engaging in strategic communication, serving the common good, and promoting purposeful living.\u201d\n\n===Institution Values===\n\n*Lifelong learning and education of the whole person  \n*Pursuit of truth and dignity  \n*Commitment to students  \n*Justice  \n*Gratitude  \n*Hospitality  \n*Service\n\n==Institutional Awards==\n\n*Named a 2019\u201320 College of Distinction based on engaged students, great teaching, vibrant communities, and successful outcomes  \n*Named a 2020 Top 50 Best Regional Midwest University, Top 50 Best Value School, Top 50 Best College for Veterans, and Top 25 Performer on Social Mobility by U.S. News & World Report  \n*Nationally ranked student Enactus team\u2014using entrepreneurial action to transform lives and shape a better, more sustainable world  \n*Award-winning volunteerism and service-learning programs\n\n==Academics==\n\nMount Mercy offers more than 85 areas of study, organized into eight academic departments - serving traditional residential, transfer, and working adult students.\n\n===Undergraduate Programs===\n\n* Business\n* Communication, Literature & Arts\n* Education\n* History, Politics & Justice\n* Natural & Applied Sciences\n* Nursing\n* Philosophy & Religious Studies\n* Psychology, Sociology, Social Work & International Studies\n\n===Graduate and Doctorate Programs===\n\n* Master of Arts in Criminal Justice (MACJ)\n* Master of Arts in Education (MAEd)\n* Master of Arts in Marriage & Family Therapy (MFT)\n* Master of Business Administration (MBA)\n* Master of Science in Nursing (MSN)\n* Master of Strategic Leadership (MSL)\n* Doctor of Nursing Practice (DNP)\n* Doctor of Philosophy in Marriage & Family Therapy (PhD in MFT)\n\n===Online Programs===\n\n* Applied Management \n* Business \n* Human Resource Management  \n* Marketing \n* Health Care Administration \n* RN to BSN \n* Religious Studies \n* Master of Arts in Criminal Justice Master of Business Administration\n\n==Athletics==\nMount Mercy teams are known as the Mustangs. The university is a member of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] (NAIA) Division I, competing in the [[Heart of America Athletic Conference]] (HAAC). Men's sports include baseball, basketball, bowling, cross country, golf, soccer, track & field, and volleyball; while women's sports include basketball, bowling, cross country, golf, soccer, softball, track & field and volleyball. Varsity and Junior Varsity programs are available in several sports.\n[[wikt:intramural|Intramural]] activities include basketball, volleyball, golf, flag football, softball and cross country.\n\n38% of traditional undergrads are student-athletes. Mount Mercy's faculty and staff mentor program promotes success in the classroom and on the playing field .\n\n===Athletic Achievements===\n\nMount Mercy's 18 athletic teams have won 50 conference team titles and qualified for 40+ national events.\nOver 120 students have been named NAIA Scholar-Athletes in the past three years, including a record 67 in the 2018\u201319 academic year. \nIn 2018\u201319: Two NAIA national team qualifiers, 14 individual qualifiers, eight NAIA all-Americans, 67 Daktronics-NAIA Scholar-Athletes, 116 all-conference performers\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.mountmercymustangs.com/ Mount Mercy Athletics website]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Colleges and universities in Iowa}}\n{{Heart of America Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Dubuque}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Dubuque}}\n{{Women's Colleges that are Coeducational}}\n{{Conference for Mercy Higher Education}}\n}}\n{{coord|42|0|8.08|N|91|39|5.49|W|type:edu_region:US|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Mount Mercy University| ]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Education in Cedar Rapids, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1928]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Dubuque]]\n[[Category:Education in Linn County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cedar Rapids, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cedar Rapids, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Catholic universities and colleges in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Former women's universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sisters of Mercy colleges and universities]]\n[[Category:Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Mercy_University"}
